			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Take a look at this: <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">lda &lt;VRAM_UPDATE</tt><br /><br />The symbol <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">&lt;</tt> means to take only the low byte of what follows, If <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">VRAM_UPDATE=$2003</tt> this means that <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">&lt;VRAM_UPDATE</tt> is <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$03</tt>.<br /><br />There is very little reason to use <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">&lt;</tt> on an address in this way. It is only really valid if the address is on the zero page already (e.g. <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$0003</tt>), but for some reason the assembler can't identify this automatically. There is a difference in efficiency between <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">lda $03</tt> and <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">lda $0003</tt>, but the cases where the assembler cannot automate this for you are rare if you know how to declare your variables correctly, i.e. declare them above where they are used, and when importing, make sure ZP variables use <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">.importzp</tt> instead of <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">.import</tt>.<br /><br />In this case, though, you're not even gaining efficiency, you're changing the address to a different, wrong address.<br /><br /><br />Okay, now that all that's out of the way, why are you reading <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$2003</tt>? This is a register for writing the OAM address before DMA upload. What do you expect reading it to do? I expect you want a zero page variable for your <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">VRAM_UPDATE</tt>, not some register of the PPU. Isn't it supposed to be a software flag that you change when you want the next NMI routine to write new data to the PPU?<br /><br /><br />(edited to correct misspelling of .importzp)</div>

					
